The devil went down to Georgia is a very tongue in cheek song/story about a hickitsune finding a man she's fancied many a year sawing a fiddle for her deep in the woods, where the only person who could have heard it was her. Should he win he'd get the "golden hooch" (and her hand), should she win she would take his rosewood fiddle as a prize... for a few days or so before she gave it back. A few members of her immediately family took in the challenge with her when she played simply as it looked fun.

Johnny however, played that fiddle like the instrument had been made ages ago for him to play. He handily won his prize and took her hand happily, moving to live with her on a county road that was easy enough to get back to civilization with but far enough to not have any sudden guests.

Hickitsunes themselves could have been much more of a myth until prohibition hit and a large number of the fluffy gals and guys ended up sharing beds and homes with people against the law making hooch. A shiner with a fast car might be able to evade the police, but a shiner with a fox gal by his would vanish on a beam of moonlight and never be found.

Last idea to add spice to the boiling stew of hickitsunes could be that they aren't all red foxes anymore. A good strong family tree with human men interspersed as any kitsune tree would have led to more species popping up as the foxes adjusted. Grey foxes popped up, some occasional oddball foxes for the more far flung trees in places like cali with their very rarely seen island foxes. That could make for a story in itself, some man in California going out to fish and forgetting to drop his anchor, ending up on the hidden island of many short but polite foxes.

This is partly where setting compensates for either ambiguity in characterization, situations or skill sets where species plays into a significant role or stereotype, or any combination of the above. Undeveloped settings that do little to inform the plot, and characters wanting any development (or dialogue) that validates their species, are going to seem easily species-swappable. Readers notice that in our stories specifically because that's why they're reading in the first place: they want to see how skillfully we weave those animal characteristics into a coherent and relatable character. I greatly appreciate the writers who observe those details well (you each probably know if you are, pat yourselves on the backs, ya' mugs).
